<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-QuayleInterview     12-05 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle Interview,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Sees No Change in Soviet Foreign Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-NATO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle says the Soviet
Union's foreign policy is largely unchanged and he believes the
Soviets' pursuit of their interests creates instability in other
countries, according to a report Tuesday.
   In remarks reflecting more apparent skepticism than President
Bush has shown about Soviet intentions, Quayle said the Soviets
have ``very significant interests beyond their borders and those
interests create instability.''
   ``I don't think they've changed much in foreign policy,'' Quayle
said in an interview with The Washington Post in Tuesday editions.
   ``We cannot count on the Soviets, out of the goodness of their
hearts, in alleviating those tensions for us.''
   But Quayle said he viewed events in one area beyond the borders
of the Soviet Union, Eastern Europe, as reflecting Soviet domestic
policy.
   ``I get into debates on this with people (in the administration)
who ask about Eastern Europe,'' Quayle was quoted as saying.
   Though Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev has been very helpful
in spurring Communist governments in Eastern Europe to reform, ``I
don't view that as a matter of foreign policy as much as domestic
policy.''
   ``My viewpoint is the new thinking and the real reform is in the
area of economics,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle said he ``hadn't seen any evidence of their slackening
off'' aid to Cuba and Nicaragua.
   On the summit meeting of President Bush and Gorbachev, Quayle
said he thought a strategic arms agreement ``is something that
could be achieved'' on the timetable agreed to by the two leaders.
   Bush told a news conference in Brussels on Monday the West
stands ``at the threshold of a new era'' but he declined to endorse
Gorbachev's suggestion that the Cold War is over. ``That day hasn't
arrived,'' Bush said.
 
</TEXT>
