<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     12-05 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Back to the Future' Reprises First Place Finish in Holiday Sweepstakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Back to the Future Part II'' came back in its
second weekend to earn $12.1 million, taking the No. 1 spot in
weekend box office receipts while ``National Lampoon's Christmas
Vacation'' earned a merry $11.7 million.
   The second installment of Steven Spielberg's ``Future'' trilogy
also ranked first the previous week during the long Thanksgiving
holiday weekend. It held its place while Chevy Chase carried
``Christmas'' nearly to the top with his comic fable of Christmas
at the Griswold household.
   In third place was Eddie Murphy's gangster saga ``Harlem
Nights,'' with $5.2 million.
   The all-woman power team of ``Steel Magnolias,'' which features
Shirley MacLaine, Sally Field and Dolly Parton, earned $4.8 million
after adding 143 screens since last weekend.
   Disney's ``The Little Mermaid'' feature-length cartoon earned $4
million for fifth place, while ``Look Who's Talking,'' John
Travolta's comeback comedy about a baby with Bruce Willis' vocal
chords earned $3.7 million for sixth.
   In seventh place was the season's other animated release, ``All
Dogs Go To Heaven,'' earning $2.2 million in ticket sales. Another
holiday family feature, ``Prancer,'' about one of Santa's reindeer,
was in eighth with $1.9 million.
   In ninth place was the family comedy-drama ``Dad,'' featuring
$1.3 million in weekend earnings and a critically acclaimed
performance by Jack Lemmon.
   The live-action animal story, ``The Bear,'' rounded out the top
ten with $1 million in receipts.
   Here are the top movie ticket sales for Friday through Sunday as
tallied by Entertainment Data and Exhibitor Relations, with
distributor, weekend gross, number of theater screens, average per
screen, total gross and number of weeks in release.
   Figures are based on a combination of actual box-office receipts
and studio projections where actual figures are not immediately
available.
   1. ``Back to the Future Part II,'' Universal, $12.1 million,
1,866 screens, $6,490 per screen, $60 million, two weeks.
   2. ``National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation,'' Warner Bros.,
$11.7 million, 1,744 screens, $6,737 per screen, $11.7 million, one
week.
   3. ``Harlem Nights,'' Paramount, $5.2 million, 2,180 screens,
$2,386 per screen, $45.5 million, three weeks.
   4. ``Steel Magnolias,'' Tri-Star, $4.8 million, 963 screens,
$5,043 per screen, $22.6 million, three weeks.
   5. ``The Little Mermaid,'' Disney, $4.0 million, 999 screens,
$4,034 per screen, $22.1 million, three weeks.
   6. ``Look Who's Talking,'' Tri-Star, $3.7 million, 1,649
screens, $2,255 per screen, $101.5 million, eight weeks.
   7. ``All Dogs Go to Heaven,'' MGM-UA, $2.2 million, 1,591
screens, $1,417 per screen, $14.1 million, three weeks.
   8. ``Prancer,'' Orion, $1.9 million, 1,728 screens, $1,117 per
screen, $10.6 million, three weeks.
   9. ``Dad,'' Universal, $1.3 million, 1,123 screens, $1,235 per
screen, $17 million, six weeks.
   10. ``The Bear,'' Tri-Star, $1 million, 1,056 screens, $1,024
per screen, $25 million, six weeks.
</TEXT>
