<FIRST>r a PM-PresidentialAirways     12-05 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Presidential Airways,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Feeder Ceases Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HERNDON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential Airways Inc., which filed for
protection from creditors under the bankruptcy laws five weeks ago,
is discontinuing all its flights.
   ``Our Chapter 11 filing has resulted in a reduction in our
passenger loads,'' president and chief executive officer Harold J.
``Hap'' Pareti said Monday.
   ``At this point it is prudent for the company to conserve as
much of its cash as possible. We will review our options for the
future to determine what is the best course to take,'' he said in a
statement.
   The service was discontinued effective Monday.
   Presidential began four years ago as a mid-size carrier,
switched to a charter service and then to a feeder service for
Continental Airlines, which then maintained a hub at Washington
Dulles International Airport at Herndon.
   However, Houston-based Continental closed its Washington hub,
and in January 1988 Presidential became a feeder for United. It
recently had been operating 24 flights a day to and from six cities.
   According to court documents, Presidential had $30 million in
assets and $76 million in liabilities as of June 30. Its largest
creditor, British Aerospace PLC, is owed about $26 million for
aircraft, the documents said.
</TEXT>
