<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     12-05 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel to Hear Testimony of USS Iowa Skipper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate panel studying the blast aboard the
USS Iowa that killed 47 sailors last April will hear testimony next
Monday from the skipper of the battleship.
   Capt. Fred P. Moosally will answer questions at the panel's
second hearing, it was announced Monday. The committee heard
testimony last month from Rear Adm. Richard Milligan, who oversaw
the Navy's technical and criminal investigation of the blast.
   The Navy concluded in its Sept. 7 report that gunner's mate
Clayton Hartwig ``most likely'' caused the explosion by inserting
some type of detonator between bags of gunpowder in one of the
ship's 16-inch guns. Hartwig was among those killed.
   Milligan told the committee that additional technical tests
conducted since the report found ``unique foreign material'' that
would not have been present during a normal firing.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Partial Merger of Las Vegas Newspapers Recommended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two daily newspapers in Las Vegas could
combine commercial and production facilities but continue
publishing separate editions under a plan that has been recommended
by the Justice Department's anti-trust division.
   Assistant Attorney General James F. Rill recommended Monday that
the Las Vegas Sun and the Las Vegas Review Journal be allowed to
make the partial merger under a joint operating agreement.
   Rill found that because of circulation and advertising losses,
the Las Vegas Sun was ``in probable danger of financial failure''
and therefore qualified for the anti-trust exemption granted by the
Newspaper Preservation Act.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh must make the final decision
whether to allow the proposed joint operating agreement to proceed.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Transportation Secretary Predicts Tests Will Show High Drug Use</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner
predicts that random drug tests for those responsible for
transportation on land, sea and air will show an ``alarming
amount'' of drug use among the workers.
   Rules begin going into effect in two weeks that require random
and other drug tests for millions of airline, railroad, mass
transit, bus company, boat, trucking company and pipeline employees.
   Skinner said Monday that where court orders do not stop the
testing, companies must comply with the new rule. Several suits
have been filed by workers to stop the federally imposed program.
Startup dates for the testing vary by modes of transportation.
   The secretary said he has set up a group in his office to
monitor progress of the testing, while agencies dealing with
aviation, railroads and other modes would each oversee industries
they cover.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Record $98 Million Collected for Hugo, California Quake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Red Cross collections for the victims of
Hurricane Hugo, the California earthquake and other recent
disasters brought in a record $98 million, officials say.
   So far, the amount raised exceeds the $94 million the group
expects to spend to help victims of the emergencies, American Red
Cross officials said Monday.
   The relief organization projects it will spend $72 million to
help people victimized by Hugo, $16 million for the San Francisco
Bay area earthquake, and $6 million for floods in Kentucky, Texas
and Louisiana, tornadoes in Alabama and other problems.
   The money goes for food, clothing, household and medical
purchases, rent, temporary repairs and other items.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
