<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-05 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Rise in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended at a
new high.
   The dollar closed at 143.68 yen, up 0.20 yen from Monday's close
of 143.48 yen. It started at 143.70 yen and ranged between 143.67
yen and 143.85 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 190.30
points, or 0.51 percent, ending at 37,494.17, yet another high. It
had climbed 171.19 points Monday.
   The index rose as soon as trading started, as market players
were reassured by the strength of overseas markets overnight, said
an analyst with Nomura Securities on condition of anonymity.
   Steel, construction and some machinery issues attacted
participants, he said.
   Other dealers said some participants sold stocks for
profit-taking after the recent increase in the index.
   Foreign exchange trading was quiet in the absence of fresh
market-affecting news, said Toru Kanai, a currency analyst with New
Japan Securities Co.
   ``Trading was very boring, and there is no news until Friday,
when the U.S. unemployment figure comes out,'' he said.
   The United States is to release the nation's monthly jobless
rate for November in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
