<FIRST>r i PM-APragueDay     12-05 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-A Prague Day,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tennis, Rock, History: Chilly Scenes of Prague's Winter</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fog-shrouded streets were
empty, unpounded this day by the hundreds of thousands who had
successfully pressed the ruling Communists to abandon one-party
rule.
   Only tourists, pub crawlers and window shoppers, bundled against
the damp cold, strolled past the Christmas displays on downtown
streets Sunday, when authorities announced a coalition Cabinet
still dominated by Communists.
   Most Czechs and Slovaks were at home, and when the announcement
came many were watching on television a tennis match or a concert
in Prague's Sports Stadium that benefited the opposition coalition
Civic Forum.
   Before 20,000 people at the stadium, a rock band turned up its
amplifiers to blast out its angry response to the government: a
spirited rendition of the Rolling Stones song, ``(I Can't Get No)
Satisfaction.''
   The crowd roared in approval, a harbinger of the massive
anti-government demonstrations that resumed Monday.
   Few people on the streets Sunday or in the smoky cafes and bars
were impressed by the government move, and others strolled on
unaware.
   Life around the Hradcany Castle went on as usual, with parents
out for the afternoon, their kids stopping to gawk at the
ceremonial guard outside the presidential residence. Only the odd
leaflet glued to a doorway, or a dab of colorful graffito, recalled
two weeks of unprecedented public protest.
   In the magnificent Old Town square, a large group of American
tourists _ guidebooks in hand _ seemed more interested in the
Middle Ages than the peaceful revolution at hand. One woman, on
learning that an American passer-by was a journalist, asked: ``Oh,
why are you here?''
   At Slavia, an elegant old cafe across from the National Theater,
a blend of Prague's golden youth and its punk culture ate up all
the ice cream by 10 p.m. Their talk of politics was leavened by
peals of laughter.
   After the government announcement, scores of pro-democracy
activists gathered at the Civic Forum headquarters to plan strategy.
   Outside the Laterna Magika theater, hundreds stood shivering to
watch videotaped opposition statements from televisions set up in
upper floor windows.
   In the early evening, opposition leaders denounced the
Communist-dominated Cabinet on national television and called for a
general strike if a new government more to their liking is not
seated.
   On another channel, West Germany's Boris Becker and Sweden's
Stefan Edberg were locked in a bitter second set in the finals of
the Masters tennis tournament from New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891205-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-89 0300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneStrike     12-05 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Strike,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Return to Jobs, Telephone Company Tackles Backlog</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Telephone workers returning to work after a
14-week strike faced a huge backlog of requests for installation,
service and other work.
   ``Everybody's now back to work. We are delighted to see them
all. The priority is attacking this backlog,'' Nynex Corp.
spokesman John Bonomo said Monday.
   The strike by about 40,000 members of the Communications Workers
of America, employed by Nynex subsidiary New York Telephone, and
20,000 members of the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers, at New England Telephone, affected 10 million customers.
   It began Aug. 6 and was the last of four regional phone company
strikes to be resolved. The IBEW and New England Telephone did not
settle until Nov. 20. The CWA ratified its contract Friday.
   New York Telephone said it was trying to fill more than 100,000
service orders and a potential backlog of another 150,000
installations with customers who withheld orders during the work
stoppage.
   Filling those orders will take until May, the company said.
Repair work, it said, is up to date.
   During the strike, some 10,000 managers filled in for striking
workers. One striker was killed in a strike-related car accident,
and Nynex claimed hundreds of acts of sabotage were made against
its property.
   A major sticking point was a proposal by the company that
workers share the cost of health care. Nynex conceded this point in
exchange for reduced wage increases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
